It doesn&#39;t throw an interrupted exception - it potentially can so at runtime. So you need to wrap it. 

You can create a function that has the try catch and call that instead of writing try catch each time like
```
void dontCareSleep(long time) {
try { Thread.sleep(time) } catch (Exception e) {}
}
```
Now you can use this method everywhere 

Another option is to use kotlin instead where the sleep doesn&#39;t need to be try caught everytime

Just write a method or lambda. You can put it in your library.
```
public static void sleep(long mill){
  try {
     Thread.sleep(mill);
  } catch(InterruptedException e){
       Thread.currentThread()
             .interrupt();
  }
}
```
Or create a lambda.  Here a `LongConsumer` is used.
```
LongConsumer sleep = (delay) -&gt; {
     try {
         Thread.sleep(delay);
     } catch (InterruptedException e) { 
        Thread.currentThread()
              .interrupt(); 
 };
```
And invoke it as follows:
```
sleep.accept(1000);

Anytime you want to do a certain task many times, you write a method, instead of copy/pasting the same code over and over. &quot;Just sleep for a little bit&quot; sounds like a very simple job but it really isn&#39;t, so, into a method it goes!

```
/**
 * Pauses this thread for {@code millis} milliseconds.
 *
 * If interrupted, the thread restarts immediately, and the
 * interruption flag remains set.
 */
public static void sleep(long millis) {
  try {
    Thread.sleep(millis);
  } catch (InterruptedException e) {
    // Best course of action is to stop sleeping but propagate
    // the interruption so the caller gets to deal with it.
    Thread.currentThread().interrupt();
  }
}

There are two methods:

### 1) Coroutines

Try using `coroutines` to work with. It&#39;s easy and will not block your main thread

Call function

    addDelay(500) {
        // showToast
    }

Declare function

    fun addDelay(timeMillis: Int = 1000, callback: () -&gt; Unit) {
        CoroutineScope(Dispatchers.Main).launch {
            delay(timeMillis.toLong())
            callback.invoke()
        }
    }

### 2) Handler

Call function

    withDelay(500) {
        // showToast
    }

Declare function

    fun withDelay(timeMillis: Int = 1000, callback: () -&gt; Unit) {
        Handler(Looper.getMainLooper()).postDelayed(block, timeMillis)
    }

There is a even better option without using Thread.sleep() (which creates flakiness especially in tests) --&gt; use Awaitility library, specially created to handle asynchronous calls.

here is an example for what are you trying to accomplish:

    await().pollDelay(1000, MILLISECONDS).untilAsserted(() -&gt; Assert.assertTrue(true));

It will check the assert (which is always true) after a delay of 1s.

You can create a method for it if you need to do it multiple times with different delay values:

        public void sleep( int delayValue) {
    
            await().pollDelay(delayValue, MILLISECONDS).untilAsserted(() -&gt; Assert.assertTrue(true));
    }

This library offers solutions also for other scenarios, for example if you want to wait for method to be executed first you can do:

    @Test
    public void updatesCustomerStatus() {
        // Publish an asynchronous message to a broker (e.g. RabbitMQ):
        messageBroker.publishMessage(updateCustomerStatusMessage);
    
        // Awaitility lets you wait until the asynchronous operation completes:
        await().atMost(5, SECONDS).until(customerStatusIsUpdated());
        
    }

See more usage scenarios on their website.

